{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638756"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:59:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:59:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17736"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17736"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.16,0.05,0.07,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74803"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10450"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17736"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60289"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"476"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24399"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24401"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74803"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy presented to his General Practitioner with fever and sore throat 2 days ago. He was prescribed antibiotics as he was thought to have bacterial tonsilitis. His mother returns today asking for a different antibiotic as she thinks he may be allergic to the one he was prescribed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antibiotics should be avoided in a patient with infectious mononucleosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amoxicillin","Doxycycline","Cefalexin","Clarithromycin","Clindamycin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and examination findings suggestive of infectious mononucleosis, commonly caused by the Epstein-Barr virus. In such cases, the use of \u003Cstrong\u003Eamoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with a high risk of developing a maculopapular rash. This reaction is not an allergic response but rather a drug-virus interaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is first-line therapy for treating infections caused by tick-borne diseases e.g. Rickettsia, Ehrlichia, Anaplasma and Lyme disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECefalexin\u003C/strong\u003E is a cephalosporin antibiotic that can be used for bacterial infections but is not typically associated with the rash seen with amoxicillin in infectious mononucleosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClarithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is a macrolide antibiotic that can be used in patients with penicillin allergies or for atypical bacterial infections. It does not cause the rash associated with amoxicillin in infectious mononucleosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClindamycin\u003C/strong\u003E is an antibiotic used for certain bacterial infections, particularly those caused by anaerobic bacteria. It is not associated with the rash seen with amoxicillin in infectious mononucleosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Amoxicillin should be avoided in patients with suspected infectious mononucleosis due to the risk of developing a rash.","Infectious mononucleosis is caused by the Epstein-Barr virus and can present with symptoms similar to bacterial tonsillitis.","A rash following amoxicillin administration in the context of infectious mononucleosis is not an allergic reaction but a drug-virus interaction."],"references":["Mergoum AM. Amoxicillin Rash in Infectious Mononucleosis. N Engl J Med. 2021 Sep 9;385(11):1033. doi: 10.1056/NEJMicm2104358. PMID: 34496177.","\u00d3nodi-Nagy K, Kiny\u00f3 \u00c1, Meszes A, Garaczi E, Kem\u00e9ny L, Bata-Cs\u00f6rg\u0151 Z. Amoxicillin rash in patients with infectious mononucleosis: evidence of true drug sensitization. Allergy Asthma Clin Immunol. 2015 Jan 9;11(1):1. doi: 10.1186/1710-1492-11-1. PMID: 25784943; PMCID: PMC4362637.","Abreu A, Nunes S, Botelho C. Eosinophilia in Amoxicillin-Induced Rash in Infectious Mononucleosis. Cureus. 2023 Jan 8;15(1):e33504. doi: 10.7759/cureus.33504. PMID: 36756024; PMCID: PMC9904423."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60289"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17736"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60289"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T09:49:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T19:02:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10450"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74803"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"re